# HA Integration Patterns

## Config entry lifecycle
- `async_setup_entry` creates `SamsungTVCoordinator`, stores in `entry.runtime_data`
- `async_unload_entry` calls `coordinator.async_shutdown()` then unloads platforms
- Never store state in module-level globals — always on the coordinator

## Coordinator pattern
`SamsungTVCoordinator` is NOT a `DataUpdateCoordinator` (no polling).
It is push-based: WebSocket events drive state changes.
Entities register via `coordinator.async_add_listener(callback)` and
call `async_write_ha_state()` from the callback.

## Entity rules
- `_attr_has_entity_name = True` on all entities
- `_attr_unique_id = f"{entry.entry_id}_{platform}"` pattern
- `DeviceInfo` uses `identifiers={(DOMAIN, entry.entry_id)}`
- No `should_poll` override needed — entities are push-updated

## Services
- Registered in `__init__.py` `_register_services()` — idempotent check first
- Schema defined with `voluptuous`; also documented in `services.yaml`
- Services operate on all entries if `entry_id` is omitted (broadcast)

## Token rotation
When the TV sends a new token in `ms.channel.connect`, call:
```python
hass.config_entries.async_update_entry(entry, data={**entry.data, CONF_TOKEN: token})
```
This persists it immediately so it survives HA restarts.
Never store the token in entity state or attributes — only in config-entry data.

## Timers
Use `hass.loop.call_later(delay, sync_callback)` where sync_callback
calls `asyncio.ensure_future(async_method())`.
Always cancel timers in `_cancel_all_timers()` before state transitions.

## Platform files
- `media_player.py` — `MediaPlayerEntity`, power + volume + source
- `remote.py` — `RemoteEntity`, key sending, rich `extra_state_attributes` for custom panel

## HA events fired
- `samsungtv_max_apps_updated` — when app catalog refreshes
- `samsungtv_max_key_sent` — (future) when a key is sent
- `samsungtv_max_app_launched` — (future) when an app is launched
